`IFormFile` buffers the entire body into memory — that's your OOM. Instead, read the raw multipart stream section-by-section and write each chunk to disk.

**Key changes:**

1. **Disable the default form body size limit:**

```csharp
// Program.cs
app.MapPost("/upload", HandleUpload)
   .DisableAntiforgery()
   .WithMetadata(new DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute());
```

Also in config (Kestrel defaults cap at ~28 MB):

```csharp
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
{
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});
```

2. **Stream multipart sections to disk without buffering:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;

async Task<IResult> HandleUpload(HttpRequest request)
{
    if (!request.HasFormContentType ||
        !MediaTypeHeaderValue.TryParse(request.ContentType, out var mt) ||
        string.IsNullOrEmpty(mt.Boundary.Value))
    {
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart/form-data request.");
    }

    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(mt.Boundary).Value!;
    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) is not null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var cd) ||
            !cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            continue; // skip non-file fields
        }

        var trustedName = Path.GetRandomFileName();          // never trust client name
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", trustedName);

        await using var outStream = File.Create(savePath);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(outStream);           // streams in 80 KB chunks
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
}
```

**Why this works:** `MultipartReader` reads the raw request stream section by section — no in-memory buffer of the full file. `CopyToAsync` streams through an 81,920-byte internal buffer by default.

**Checklist you should also handle in production:**
- Validate `section.Headers["Content-Length"]` or count bytes during copy to enforce the 2 GB cap per-file.
- Sanitize / ignore the client-supplied filename (`cd.FileName`).
- Consider streaming to a temp file first, then renaming on success.
- Add a `CancellationToken` from `HttpContext.RequestAborted`.
